\subsection{Comparing with Random Matrix Theory predictions}

Now we turn from the raw data associated to twists of these three types of L-functions and to the comparison of these data with the corresponding data from random matrix theory.  In this section we do not concern ourselves with excising the model, we pick that up in the next section.

\subsubsection{Matrix groups calculations}
As explained in \ncr{Section 6.6}, just after Corollary 8, the L-functions corresponding to forms $f$ where $\chi_f$ is principal correspond to matrices in the group $\textrm{SO}(\text{even})$, forms $f$ that are self-dual and have non-principal $\chi_f$ correspond to matrices in $\textrm{U}(N)$ \ncr{even?} and forms $f$ that are not self-dual and have non-principal $\chi_f$ correspond to matrices in $\textrm{USp}(2N)$ \ncr{even?}.  We implemented an algorithm for each group in Sage; the algorithm is described in \cite{mezzadri}.  See Figure~\ref{fig:densities} for density plots of $100,000$ $50\times 50$ matrices from each group.
\begin{figure}
\centering
\begin{minipage}{.3\textwidth}
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{SO50.png}
\end{minipage}
\begin{minipage}{.3\textwidth}
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{U50.png}
\end{minipage}
\begin{minipage}{.3\textwidth}
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{USp50.png}
\end{minipage}
\caption{Density plots of 100,000 $50\times 50$ matrices in (from the left) the special orthogonal group, the unitary and the unitary sympletic group.  The shape of the curve matches the predictions in \ncr{Corollary 8}.\ncr{I need to regenerate nicer plots here}}\label{fig:densities}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Trivial nebentypus}

Let $f$ be as in Section~\ref{sec:repulsion1}. Let $\mathscr{D}_f (X )$ be as in \ncr{Definition 4} for $\chi_f$ principal. We calculate the distribution of the lowest zero for $L(s, f \otimes \psi_d )$ for $d \in \mathscr{D}_f (X )$, provided $L(1/2, f \otimes \psi_d ) \neq 0$. We also also calculate the distribution of the lowest eigenvalue for $\textrm{SO}(2N_{\text{std}} )$ where $N_\text{std}$ for discriminants around $X$ is given by 
\[
N_\text{std} = \log\left (\frac{\sqrt{3}X}{2\pi e}\right ).
\]
In Figure~\ref{fig:exp1-comp} we show the same zeros as in Figure~\ref{fig:trivial} and a plot of the distribution for random matrices in $\textrm{SO}(8)$ since $N_\text{std}$ for $X \approx 40,000$ is $3.6\dots$. The plots have been normalized to as to have the same mean.  We observe that the match between the two distributions is pretty good.  In a later section we sample differently and get a better fit; see Section~\ref{sec:excise1}.
\begin{figure}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{exp1-comp.png}
\end{center}
\caption{A comparison of lowest positive eigenangle in $\textrm{SO}(8)$ and $\mathscr{F}_f$ where $f$ is as in Section~\ref{sec:repulsion1}.  The two graphs have been normalized to have the same mean.}\label{fig:exp1-comp}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Self-dual, non-trivial nebentypus} 

Let $f$ be as in Section~\ref{sec:repulsion2}. Let $\mathscr{D}_f (X )$ be as in \ncr{Definition 4} for $\chi_f$ non-trivial. We calculate the distribution of the lowest zero for $L(s, f \otimes \psi_d )$ for $d \in \mathscr{D}_f (X )$, provided $L(1/2, f \otimes \psi_d ) \neq 0$. We also also calculate the distribution of the lowest eigenvalue for $\textrm{U}(N_{\text{std}} )$ where $N_\text{std}$ for discriminants around $X$ is once again given by 
\[
N_\text{std} = \log\left (\frac{\sqrt{3}X}{2\pi e}\right ).
\]
In Figure~\ref{fig:exp2-comp} we show the same zeros as in Figure~\ref{fig:trivial} and a plot of the distribution for random matrices in $\textrm{U}(4)$ since $N_\text{std}$ for $X \approx 40,000$ is $3.6\dots$. The plots have been normalized to as to have the same mean.  We observe that the match between the two distributions is pretty good.  
